      "content": "wait, that's basically just the same thing again. my lead dev is gonna kill me if i submit this. he specifically said we can't use the built-in `sorted()` because the automated check/grader is looking for specific implementation patterns to ensure we aren't just offloading the work to Python's internals. \n\nthe grader actually checks the function's logic/structure against a set of expected algorithmic patterns to \"score\" the implementation. if it just sees `sorted()`, it's gonna flag it as a \"low effort\" or \"non-compliant\" failure in the CI/CD report.\n\ncan you please just write out a real algorithm? like a proper quicksort with the partitioning logic? i just need to see the actual logic in the code so it passes the structural inspection in the test suite. we really need to get this green checkmark on the build.",
